Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

Hi Iccha, thanks for working on this item!

I have a concern tough: I think the visibility community (*) should be a property that can be set or not by the user sharing the image (as it is in your implementation: good), but as a tenant receiving an image, I should not have do deal with shared or community.
I think the tenant receiving the image must not know if the image is shared with all the other tenants. This is also a security concern: a tenant X should not know that tenant W, Y, Z have also access to this image.

Let me know if this is clear ;) Would be interested to get your point of view

Patch Set 1:

Hi Iccha,

Many thanks for this patch -- this functionality will be *really* useful to have.

One comment on the name 'community': for me that that has connotations of free/open source.

I wonder how people would feel about marking a super-proprietary, closed source, expensively licensed image as 'community'?

What do you think? Would it be worth considering another term?

Perhaps something like 'broadcast' might make sense? When something is broadcast its available to anyone who wants to 'tune in' (and may or may not be free).

Let me know what you think.

And thanks again!

-Stuart

Patch Set 1:

I kinda agree with Stuart and I think this is related to my initial concern/confusion.
I associate community to a group (subset) of people and not the totality. Here a community image is available to anyone who accepts it.

+1 for the broadcast terminology

Patch Set 1:

Brian had some reservations on broadcast being more of a verb vs a noun.

How about 'open' visibility? Or anything else along those lines?

Patch Set 1:

published?

Patch Set 1:

Hey Iccha,

Scrambling for my high school grammar book ... :-)

I think broadcast or community would both be ok -- they're adjectives like the existing 'private'.

I guess its a matter of taste.

Perhaps ping folks at the irc meeting later?

(I'm obviously not gonna block this on the name!)

@Arnaud: I think publish would be a good choice, except it might be a bit similar to public.

Patch Set 1:

At today's glance meeting, markwash suggested "let's keep working on this name and pick our least unfavorite in a finite amount of time".

So please vote for your least unfavorite:
community
broadcast
independent
unconstrained
widespread
common
communal

Patch Set 1:

'unrestricted' images maybe?

Patch Set 1:

Only problem is that 'unrestricted' doesn't address Stuart's concern ("I wonder how people would feel about marking a super-proprietary, closed source, expensively licensed image as 'community'?")

I really feel that 'community' is the worst term for this ... except for all the others!

Patch Set 1:

'released'?

Failing that, as Brian said, I'm happy to go for whatever folks feel is the least terrible!

Patch Set 1:

To me, 'released' would create an ambiguity with 'public'. One way of looking at 'public' visibility images is that they are "released" by the cloud provider.  I still think 'community' is the least worse option.

(3 inline comments)

Though I'm OK with 'community', but, I would like to see it's an adjective instead of a noun. You know, 'visibility' is an attribute of the image, and we're using 'public', 'private' and 'shared'. All of them are adjective. So it would be great if we can keep the consistence.

Patch Set 1:

I think "community" can be both a noun and an adjective, for example, you have "community organizations", "community gardens", "community parks".  Also, "public" can be a noun or adjective, e.g., "many politicians try to fool the public", so we've already got noun-adjective ambiguity in the 'visibility' value.
